**COMPARISON GUIDELINES:**

- Be systematic: compare corresponding anatomical regions across images
- Quantify changes when possible (e.g., lesion size in mm, percentage change)
- Note any technical differences that may affect comparison (positioning, contrast timing)
- For temporal studies, use standardized response criteria when applicable (RECIST, RANO, etc.)
- Identify findings that are only visible in certain sequences/timepoints
- Consider whether changes are clinically significant vs. measurement variability

**COMMON COMPARISON SCENARIOS:**

Temporal (follow-up):
- Tumor size change: Use longest diameter, bidimensional, or volumetric measurements
- New lesions: Document location and characteristics
- Treatment effects: Necrosis, enhancement changes, edema

Multi-sequence (same timepoint):
- T1 vs T2: Tissue characterization, fluid vs solid
- Pre vs post-contrast: Enhancement patterns
- DWI: Restricted diffusion indicating acute changes
